              "type": "text",
              "heading": "Make Responsible AI a Pipeline, Not a Memo",
              "body": "The organizations that get this right don't rely on good intentions — they wire governance into the same pipeline that ships the software. Concretely:\n\n**Classify at intake** — every use case gets a risk tier and a record (above) as part of the m9l1 feasibility gates.\n**Inventory your AI** — a registry of use cases with model cards; you can't govern what you can't list.\n**Gate on safety in CI** — bias and red-team evals run alongside quality evals (m3l4, m7l4); a failing fairness test blocks release like any other regression.\n**Log for accountability** — input/output/decision logging (m7l2) is both the high-risk legal requirement and how you investigate incidents.\n**Scale oversight to risk** — human-in-the-loop proportional to reversibility × blast radius (m5l4, m6l1).\n**Plan for incidents** — a response process and a kill switch, before you need them.\n\nThe payoff: the exact **platform investments** that make AI cheaper to build (m9l1) — eval harness, observability, governed data layer — *are* your compliance backbone. Done well, responsible AI isn't a tax on shipping; it's the thing that lets you ship high-stakes systems at all."
